 Frantz Fanon, René Maran, Jomo Kenyatta, and Claude McKay, Macharia moves through genres—psychoanalysis, fiction, anthropology, poetry—as well as regional geohistories across Africa and Afro-diaspora to map the centrality of sex, gender, desire, and eroticism to black freedom struggles. In lyrical, meditative prose, Macharia invigorates frottage as both metaphor and method with which to rethink diaspora by reading, and reading against, discomfort, vulnerability, and pleasure.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh  aJamaica.  aKenya.  aKikuyu.  aaesthetics.  aanthropology.  acolonial modernity.  aderacination.  adesire.  aerotic.  aethnicity.  aethnography.  ahomosexual.  akinship.  amourning.  apoetry.  apunishment.  athinghood.  atouch.  aungendering.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479861675.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479861675423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479861675/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles